# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Perth, Western Australia, from 22 November to 1 December 1962.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Athletic events were held at Perry Lakes Stadium in the suburb of Floreat and swimming events at Beatty Park in North Perth.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was held after the 1962 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Most venues other than the specifically constructed Lake Monger Velodrome, Beatty Park, and Perry Lakes Stadium, were existing facilities.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 35 teams were represented at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Note: The medals used at these Games were the first to have a neck chain.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] All previous games had their medals in presentation boxes.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The **First Commonwealth Paraplegic Games** were held in Perth, Western Australia, from 10 to 17 November 1962.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] These Games preceded the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games which were held in Perth from 22 November to 1 December of that year.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The Commonwealth Paraplegic Games were conceived by George Bedbrook after Perth won the right to host the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Great support was received from Royal Perth Hospital, a leading spinal rehabilitation centre in Australia.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] These games raised the profile of paraplegic (spinal cord and polio) athletes in Australia, particularly Western Australia.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The chairman of the Organising Committee, Hugh Leslie, who had lost a leg in World War II, gave a speech aimed to change public perceptions about disabilities by addressing the power of language.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] These games, he told the audience, "were designed to prove to the public that the person who was bodily handicapped was not a cripple, and he hoped that that horrible word would eventually be wiped out of use.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] He had a slogan which he hoped would be adopted by all disabled: 'I can, I will'".
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Leading officials such as Bedbrook, the founder of the Stoke Mandeville Games, were impressed with the spectator turnout.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Although the standards were lower than those of the Stoke Mandeville Games, there were some outstanding individual performances and several world records were broken.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] It was decided to hold the games in Perth because the city was to host the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games and Royal Perth Hospital had a well developed spinal unit that could support paraplegic athletes.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The Commonwealth Paraplegic Games were held before the main Games as to not impact on this event and provide the opportunity for athletes to stay on for the main Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The Royal Perth Hospital board of management were the official sponsors of the event and established an organising committee in 1959.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The Australian Paraplegic Council was not formed until February 1962.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The main members of the organising committee were Hugh Leslie (executive chairman), George Bedbrook (general secretary) and M.R.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The appointment of Hugh Leslie, a leg amputee, as chairman was important due to his influence as a member of the Parliament of Australia, his previous experience with paraplegic sporting teams and as a champion of people with a disability.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The organising committee paid for all costs incurred in Australia to participating countries.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] They were only required to pay their transport and stop over costs to and from Australia.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Other Australian states were consulted and requested to provide funding of A£9,250.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The specific state funding quotas were £2,500 for Victoria, £2,500 for New South Wales, £2,600 for Western Australia, £1,000 for Queensland and £450 for South Australia.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] There was a concern as to not impact on the fundraising required by the Commonwealth Games appeal.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Several reports of the games highlight the importance of large spectator attendance and 'passing the hat' around in the fundraising efforts.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The total cost at the games was £11,717 with a surplus of £2,089.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The games were opened by the Governor of Western Australia, Sir Charles Gairdner, on 10 November 1962.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] In his opening speech, Gairdner stated that "the public must learn that the handicapped person is not an invalid.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] I am handicapped, but the one thing I loathe is for people to treat me as an invalid.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] We, the public, must realise what can be done to rehabilitate people who have suffered a grievous physical disadvantage".
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The opening ceremony was described as a "colourful spectacle" due to the Army's Western Command Band wearing scarlet jackets and white helmets, the Army Guard of Honour in jungle green clothing and the blue uniforms of the mounted escort.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The order of the wheelpast was Singapore, India, New Zealand, Rhodesia, Wales, Northern Ireland, England and the host country Australia.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Hugh Leslie, the games chairman, in his speech said "This event, apart from helping the participants, is designed to prove to the public that the person who is badly handicapped is not a cripple.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The second half of the opening ceremony and the start of the competitive program was a basketball match between Australia and England.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The game was played on a special court, constructed of timber flooring laid on a sand base, at the Agricultural Showgrounds in full view of the crowd in the grandstand.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] In front of a couple of thousand spectators, with the game being called on the public address system by a television sports commentator, Allan Terry, the Australians beat the English by a single basket (20–18).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The closing ceremony, before a near-capacity crowd of 3,500, had the colour of the opening, with 35 marching bands (400 girls) and Scottish bands.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The crowd had been present for the recently completed basketball final game.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] A DC-7B aircraft, chartered by the British teams, conducted a fly past.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Each team then wheeled past the dais to the famous Australian song "Waltzing Matilda".
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Sir Arthur Porritt, chairman of the British Empire and Commonwealth Games Federation, declared the games closed.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] In his speech, he told the audience that he hoped the general public would continue to support paraplegics and their movement.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The original plan was to hold the games at the Shenton Park Annexe of Royal Perth Hospital but this was abandoned due to the need for temporary buildings.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The Royal Agricultural Showground in the suburb of Claremont was used as it had an oval and buildings for accommodation and events.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] A major advantage of the venue was that all facilities were on one level.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] There was no suitable facility for basketball and after much debate a wooden court was laid on a sand foundation in front of the main grandstand.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Beatty Park was used for swimming events.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The organising committee decided at the outset that transport would be a major issue and ultimately reflect on the success of the games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The decision to locate most of the events and accommodation at the showgrounds reduced many of the issues.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Car companies in Perth made cars available and volunteer drivers assisted in taking athletes and officials around Perth, particularly to Beatty Park.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The biggest issue was encountered by teams from the United Kingdom that had to travel 20,000 miles (32,000 km).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] A total of 57 athletes and 23 escorts travelled from the United Kingdom in a chartered Caledonian Airways plane at the cost of GB£18,500.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The long flight required refuelling in Bahrain and a stop over in Colombo, Ceylon.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Health checks such as measuring legs and ankles for swelling were undertaken during the flight to Perth and back home.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] A major logistical effort was required to transport the 80 member team to the Showgrounds on arrival at Perth airport.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Royal Perth Hospital's special coach, a Red Cross bus, private cars and a truck to carry wheelchairs were used.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The flag was the games emblem of a javelin thrower in a wheelchair with a background outline of the flag of Australia on a flagpole in a slight breeze.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Medals had one side with the games emblem and the reverse side name of sport with room for engraving.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Badges were given to each competitor and official with the aims of identification and access to the dining hall.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The badge also became a memento of the games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] A total of 89 athletes from nine countries competed.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The countries represented and their allocated colours were: England (dark blue), India (light green), New Zealand (pink), Northern Ireland (dark green), Rhodesia (light blue), Scotland (black), Singapore (red), Wales (white) and Australia (gold).
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The only major Commonwealth country not represented was Canada, which decided not to attend.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Many athletes competed in several sports because each country selected their team based on the versatility of sporting ability to reduce their team size and hence costs.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] , John Turich, John Rein, Alan Robertson (Captain), G.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] : Richard (Dick) Hollick, Anthony (Tony) Potter, Stefan Gawanick, R.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Approximately 40 attendants assisted the teams.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] There were fourteen events – archery, dartchery, javelin throw, precision javelin, club throw, shot put, swimming, weightlifting, pentathlon, fencing, snooker, basketball and table tennis.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Not all events awarded silver and bronze medals due to insufficient competitors.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Seven awards were presented during the games that reflected sporting excellence and personal endeavour.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Reflections from athletes and officials provide an insight into the value of this inaugural event.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Bill Mather-Brown, an Australian athlete, said "The 1962 Games was the first time I had been asked for an autograph.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] We were mobbed, especially at the swimming pool.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Sometimes we were not sure people really wanted our signature or were just being polite and wanted us to feel good".
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] He wanted to go back to Perth to see the Stitt family who looked after him in Perth.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The crowd's thunderous applause made the official more comfortable about the event.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Gaynor Harry, an athlete from Wales, wrote "Then was the moment to think of the fabulous organization that went into the games, from start to finish there wasn't a hitch.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] If we needed a postage stamp, that was easy.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] If licking the back of it had given us a thirst for iced water, that was easy too.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The highest tribute that can be paid is that it all appeared so effortless, as though it all just happened".
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Richard Hollick, an athlete from England, highlighted the importance of the games in self-development " Not only do we enjoy ourselves but we also learnt more about adapting ourselves than we probably normally learn in a year".
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Many athletes had to travel large distances to attend the games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Shelagh Jones, an athlete from England, wrote of the nature of competition " As the various sports on the program got under way, more and more we realised a full-blooded fight was on.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The swimming, fencing and field events arrived at the top of the sportscard in next-to-no-time and in these games we found success and failure, humour and disappointment, laughter and tears.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The spectator attendance amazed leading officials such as Ludwig Guttmann, the founder of the Stoke Mandeville Games.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] He commented that the attendance was the best he had seen at any paraplegic sports event in the world.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] The games highlighted the versatility of the athletes with many winning medals in different sports.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] It was noted that generally the standard of performance was below that of the Stoke Mandeville Games; however there were several outstanding performers including Vic Renalson, Bill Mather-Brown, Lorraine Dodd, M.
[src:1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games/1962-commonwealth-paraplegic-games] Scott who broke records in their events.
